defaultThe ddefaultepartment’s views on the impact of the abolition of the Audit Commission on the ability of defaultlocal authorities to detect and tackle fraud, including what the role of the National Audit Office should be in supporting whistleblowers and whether there are any uncertainties about the provision of an independent third party for whistleblowers to contacdefaultt if they are aware of fraud related to local authority procurement exercises (Q463)default&#xa0;
defaultIn response to the point raised by the Committee on the impact of the abolition of the Audit Commission on the ability of 
defaultcouncils
default to detect and tackle fraud we would a
defaultgr
defaultee that the Audit Commission
default has made an important contribution, not least through the requirement for all public bodies subject to audit to participate in the biannual data matching exercise carried out by the Commission’s National Fraud Initiative. Durin
defaultg the passage of the Local Audi
defaultt and Accountability Bill, the g
defaultovernment announced that the Initiative (which
default 
defaultsince its inception in 1996, has helped to identify over £1 billion of fraud, error and overpayment) and its associated data-matching powers would
default transfer to the Cabinet Office. My officials are working with the Cabinet Office to ensure a smooth transition of that important function. We are also working with the Commission to determine the future of its other counter fraud tools that matter to loca
defaultl government. Furthermore, the wider scope of public audit means that the external auditor would need to be reassured that the body had suitable counter fraud measures in place to protect public funds.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, on 10 December we announced a £16.6 mill
defaultion of new investment which will not only protect local government from the impact of the Single Fraud Investigation Service on its non-welfare counter fraud capacity, it could enable around 200 more fraud investigators to be recruited in the fight to tack
defaultle this £2 billion a year problem. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn relation to 
defaultwhistleblowing
default, we are mirroring the current arrangements. At present, the Audit Commission directs whistleblowers to the appointed auditor who is the person empowered to take any appropriate action in th
defaulte course of the audit. We will amend the order so that whistleblowers will continue to be able to go directly to their auditor and the 
defaultNational Audit Office’s
default Comptroller and Auditor General to raise concerns, when the Commission is abolished. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAny disclos
defaultures made to the 
defaultNational Audit Office
default or the appointed auditor will continue to be protected under 
defaultwhistleblowing
default legislation.
